## A brief history of Pantoum verse

The pantoum verse, or pantoum poem, is a fixed form used widely in Malay and Singapore literature and originates from the Southeast Asian region. It consists of four unrhymed stanzas and a refrain that uses the same end-words. Each stanza contains four lines, of which the second and the fourth lines rhyme with each other and the second and the fourth lines of the subsequent verse rhyme, but do not repeat the previous verse. The cause of the symptoms of anxiety can sometimes be clear. In particular if there is an underlying health problem.

> Anxiety is a physical state that is often accompanied by symptoms and effects. You may get more insecure and more tense. It is usually a temporary state.

It may look like that you are anxious for no apparent reason if you do not know the cause of anxiety. In that case, it may actually go on.

The more often you feel anxious, the more easily you will feel anxiety if a situation occurs where your body is already tense.

A great, fun and touching drama for the whole family.

Ingval and his wife Bjølve are the epitome of a couple who’ve lost everything, and can’t find their way again. Their children leave, they get divorced, and they both find new jobs and new lovers. Tommy is wounded and must be cared for by his parents, played by two more players. The parents lose the game if they are killed off by the war, and the child dies (game ends) when shot by the parent.

The game is made from hard cardboard, and the cards are printed up in 4 languages: Danish, English (Tommy is still Tommy and the game title is “Where are you wounded”), German (Tommy is now Hans) and Russian (“Where are you wounded? / What’s the matter, Tommy?”).

# Gjeldhaug’s thesis on media development in developing countries published

Freedom of expression is becoming a global human rights concern. This was confirmed by the United Nations’ Special Rapporteur on the promotion and protection of the freedom of opinion and expression, David Kaye. He visited the University of South-Eastern Norway (USN) in October 2019 to meet representatives from the national and international human rights arenas.

During that visit, Kaye was given a copy of researcher Kristin Gjeldhaug’s thesis on media development in developing countries. This has now been published by the university library of USN (USN). ## The German Occupation of Norway and German National Socialism - An Introduction

In November 1939, shortly after the outbreak of the Second World War in Europe, Germany invaded Norway. Until then Norway had not yet introduced conscription, the armed forces consisted of volunteers or reservists, and the country´s fleet was quite old-fashioned. However, the Norwegians´ attitude of not cooperating with a possible military occupation ensured a long and hard time for the Norwegian partisans during the war years.

Six months after the German attack, they had to be evacuated from mainland Norway to the neutral country Sweden. Norway stayed under German occupation until the Allied forces landed in Trondheim in 1945

### Lundberg by

The landscape of Lundberg is characterized by undulating hills and a relatively dense network of small lakes. Between and the lakes the landscape is mainly covered by forest and meadow, while larger open areas dominate in the eastern part of the by. The large open areas are used for agriculture or residential areas.

The settlement model in Lundberg by can be described with the term 'rural by'. The settlement model can be described as small, scattered villages with many farms and hamlets around. The settlements have been created at sites where resources or transport routes are advantageous. The main road between Kongsvinger and Elverum, with many small settlements in Lundberg is an example of this.

### The Rough Path Towards Freedom – A History Of The LGBTI Rights Struggle In Norway

The struggle for sexual and gender equality has been long, hard, and not easy to find any clear direction on from the outside. This publication tries to sketch this long road which has brought us, in Norway, to our current position of relative freedom and equality of gays, lesbians and all the rest of us who don’t happen to conform to the heteronormative standards. It is a history based on oral interviews with key figures in the Norwegian feminist and gay movement.
